id: AIC-VALIDATE-001
type: module
owner: business
extends: project.intent

module: aic validate
command: aic validate <intent-file-path>
description: >
  Validates a user-provided .intent file against AIC intent quality standards.
  Compares the file structure and intent language against project, language,
  and command-level guidelines. Generates AI feedback without modifying files.

behaviors:
  - id: AIC-VALIDATE-001-B1
    intent: |
      Validate that the supplied file exists and has a .intent extension.
      Reject missing files and invalid paths before contacting the AI.

  - id: AIC-VALIDATE-001-B2
    intent: |
      Parse the intent file as YAML.
      If the file is malformed, report parse errors clearly and stop.

  - id: AIC-VALIDATE-001-B3
    intent: |
      Load project.intent if present, and language.intent if the file is within
      a language folder. Use these standards as context for validation.

  - id: AIC-VALIDATE-001-B4
    intent: |
      Call the configured AI provider once with:
        1) the user intent file content
        2) standard AIC validation guidelines
        3) project/language context when available
      Ask the AI to identify missing sections, unclear wording, structural
      issues, and suggested improvements.

  - id: AIC-VALIDATE-001-B5
    intent: |
      Print the AI feedback clearly to the terminal.
      Do not modify the user's intent file automatically.

journeys:
  - actor: Developer
    trigger: Runs aic validate with a new or edited .intent file
    outcome: |
      The command returns actionable feedback on validation issues,
      helping the developer improve intent clarity and readiness for AIC.

failure-modes:
  - scenario: Intent file missing
    response: Exit with clear message and example usage.

  - scenario: Invalid YAML content
    response: Exit with parse error and avoid any AI provider call.

  - scenario: AI provider not configured
    response: Exit with instructions to populate .aic/aic.config.json.
